lementation brief" /></a>MCH systems are interdisciplinary/interprofessional (ID/IP) in nature. ID/IP practice provides a supportive environment in which the skills and expertise of team members from different disciplines, including a variety of professionals, MCH populations, and community partners, are acknowledged and seen as essential and synergistic. Input from each team member is elicited and valued in making collaborative, outcome-driven decisions to address individual, community-level, or systems-level problems<sup>2</sup>.</p>		    <p>Interest in promoting more team-based education and interprofessional learning for U.S. health professions has been an area of importance in the field for over 40 years.  The Institute of Medicine (IOM) conducted its first conference in 1972 and has convened various IOM Committees throughout the years that have produced guidelines and recommendations for how to arm health professionals with the knowledge and skills on working together and successfully implementing interprofessional collaborative practice.  Most recently, in 2011, the Interprofessional Education Collaborative convened an expert panel that developed core competencies for this topic guided by 4 domains that assist in successfully implementing skills associated with interprofessional practice<sup>3</sup>.</p>		    <p>View each of the <em>four domains</em> below and corresponding learning opportunities for: 1) Values/ethics for interprofessional practice, 2) Roles and responsibilities, 3) Interprofessional communication, and 4) Teams and teamwork.</p>						<button class="accordion">1. Values/Ethics for Interprofessional Practice:</button>					<div class="panel">						<ul>						<li><strong><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L7--0Igd0bQ&amp;t=659s">Interprofessional Education Core Competency Domain 1: Values/Ethics</a></strong>. <em>Year Developed</em>: 2016. <em>Source</em> Texas Center for Health Interprofessional Education. <em>Presenter(s)</em>: Unknown. <em>Type</em>: Video. <em>Level</em>: Introductory. <em>Length</em>: 17 minutes.</li>						<li><strong><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=abfzBXZg60s">Ethical Interprofessional Collaboration</a></strong>. <em>Year Developed</em>: 2016. <em>Source:</em> Unknown. <em>Presenter(s)</em>: Nomagugu Mafu, Michelle Manso, Liss Mathew, Amber Nelsen. <em>Type</em>: Video. <em>Level</em>: Introductory. <em>Length</em>: 12 minutes.</li>						</ul>					</div>			<button class="accordion">2.	 Roles/Responsibilities:</button>					<div class="panel">						<ul>						<li><strong><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G3add_DXZlA&amp;t=7s">Interprofessional Education Core Competency Domain 2: Roles/Responsibilities</a></strong>. <em>Year Developed</em>: 2016. <em>Source:</em> Texas Center for Health Interprofessional Education. <em>Presenter(s)</em>: Unknown. <em>Type</em>: Video. <em>Level</em>: Introductory. <em>Length</em>: 26 minutes.</li>						<li><strong><a href="https://www.mchnavigator.org/trainings/detail.php?id=1456">Bringing it All Together: An Integrated Approach</a></strong>. <em>Year Developed</em>: 2012. <em>Source:</em> North Carolina Institute for Public Health. <em>Presenter(s)</em>: Unknown. <em>Type</em>: Online Course. <em>Level</em>: Introductory. <em>Length</em>: 20 minutes.</li>						<li><strong><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Jz3KbBxy_Qw&amp;feature=youtu.be">The Why, What and How of Interprofessional Collaboration</a></strong>. <em>Year Developed</em>: 2016. <em>Source:</em> American Speech-Language-Hearing Association. <em>Presenter(s)</em>: Deborah Dixon, MA; Ellen Fagan, EdD; Lemmietta McNeily, PhD; Loretta Nunez, AuD. <em>Type</em>: Narrated Slide Presentation. <em>Level</em>: Introductory. <em>Length</em>: 105 minutes.</li>						</ul>					</div>								<button class="accordion">3. Interprofessional Communication:</button>					<div class="panel">						<ul>						<li><strong><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p75Qkn-953A">Interprofessional Education Core Competency Domain 3: Interprofessional Communication</a></strong>. <em>Year Developed</em>: 2016. <em>Source:</em> Texas Center for Health Interprofessional Education. <em>Presenter(s)</em>: Unknown. <em>Type</em>: Video. <em>Level</em>: Introductory. <em>Length</em>: 18 minutes.</li>						<li><strong><a href="https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCjsbTqos6SDEpL9Oi_28xZQ/playlists">Collaboration and Communication in Healthcare: Principles of Interprofessional Practice</a></strong>. <em>Year Developed</em>: 2016. <em>Source</em>: University of California, San Francisco, Interprofessional Education Program. <em>Presenter(s)</em>: Unknown. <em>Type</em>: Online Course. <em>Level</em>: Advanced. <em>Length</em>: Series; Varying Lengths.</li>						<li><strong><a href="http://www.jhsph.edu/research/centers-and-institutes/womens-and-childrens-health-policy-center/MCHLDS/m2.html">Creating Clarity and Shared Vision</a></strong>. <em>Year Developed</em>: 2008. <em>Source:</em> Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health, Women’s and Children’s Health Policy Center. <em>Presenter(s)</em>: Ben Lozare, PhD. <em>Type</em>: Online Course. <em>Level</em>: Introductory/Intermediate. <em>Length</em>: 240 minutes.</li>						</ul>					</div>						<button class="accordion">4. Teams and Teamwork:</button>					<div class="panel">						<ul>						<li><strong><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IRIkJKppR_8">Interprofessional Education Core Competency Domain 4: Teams and Teamwork</a></strong>. <em>Year Developed</em>: 2016. <em>Source:</em> Texas Center for Health Interprofessional Education. <em>Presenter(s)</em>: Unknown. <em>Type</em>: Video. <em>Level</em>: Introductory. <em>Length</em>: 17 minutes.</li>						<li><strong><a href="http://www.jhsph.edu/research/centers-and-institutes/womens-and-childrens-health-policy-center/MCHLDS/m3.html">Building and Supporting Teams</a></strong>. <em>Year Developed</em>: 2008. <em>Source</em>: Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health, Women’s and Children’s Health Policy Center. <em>Presenter(s)</em>: Holly Grason, MA; <em>Type</em>: Online Course. <em>Level</em>: Intermediate. <em>Length</em>: 204 minutes.</li>						<li><strong><a href="https://pace.tulane.edu/content/building-and-maintaining-collaborative-culture">Building and Maintaining a Collaborative Culture</a></strong>. <em>Year Developed</em>: 2011. <em>Source</em>: South Central Public Health Partnership. <em>Presenter(s)</em>: W. Jack Duncan, PhD; Bryn Manzella, MPH. <em>Type</em>: Narrated Slide Presentation. <em>Level</em>: Intermediate. <em>Length</em>: 120 minutes.</li>						<li><strong><a href="https://www.ahrq.gov/teamstepps/officebasedcare/index.html">TeamSTEPPS for Office-Based Care</a></strong>. <em>Year Developed</em>: 2015. <em>Source</em>: Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality. <em>Presenter(s)</em>: Unknown. <em>Type</em>: Online Course. <em>Level</em>: Intermediate/Advanced. <em>Length</em>: Self-Paced.</li>						</ul>					</div>					<hr /><p><strong>References</strong></p>			<ol>			<li>Sujata, B., Oliveras, E., and Edson, W.N. (2001). <em>How Can Self-Assessment Improve the Quality of Healthcare? </em> Operations Research Issue Paper 2(4). Published for the U.S. Agency for International Development (USAID) by the Quality Assurance (QA) Project.</li>			<li>MCH Leadership Competencies Workgroup (2018), "<a href="https://mchb.hrsa.gov/training/leadership-00.asp">MCH Leadership Competencies Version 4.0</a>".</li>			<li>Interprofessional Education Collaborative Expert Panel. (2011). Core competencies for interprofessional collaborative practice: Report of expert panel. Washington, D.C.: Interprofessional Education Collaborative.</li>			</ol>			<hr />			<p><strong>Interdisciplinary/Interprofessional Team Building: Implementation Brief</strong><br />			  <strong>Authors: </strong>Keisha Watson, Ph.D., MCH Navigator<br />			  <strong>Reviewers:</strong> Faculty and 